default1. default              default              defaultEffectiveness of Programmesdefault&#xa0;
defaultIbrahim and Beaudet in Table 1 highlight how the actions of the donor community (we include DFID) do not meet any of the six principles for effective engagement
default. 
default              
default            Table 1. Assessment of Fragile States Principles in the OPT
default             Principlesdefault                     Reality in the OPTdefault&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultTake context as the             starting pointdefaultMajor donors (the United States in particular) do not agree that 
defaultthe core problem of the OPT is occupation. The starting point remains a series of social and economic problems related to governance issues while, in reality, the perpetuation of the occupation remains the core problem.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultDo no harmdefaultDonors have done harm 
defaultby not opposing physical destruction, human rights violations and disrespect for international law perpetrated by the Israeli occupation. They have also enhanced Palestinian divisions and opposed attempts to reconcile the different factions.
default&#xa0;
defaultFocus on defaultstate-buildingdefaultPalestinians so far have been unable to build their state. Moreover, the PNA is often neglected by donors who prefer quick-impact projects either under their own direct control or through private Palestinian or foreign entities.
default&#xa0;
defaultPrioritisedefault preventiondefaultLittle preventive action was taken despite the predictability of recurring conflicts. The intensive clashes since 2000 were the result of the non-resolution of fundamental issues including the creation of an independent Palestinian state. Donor
defaults have many times focused on the consequences rather than the causes of the impasse.
default&#xa0;
defaultRecognise links between political, security and development objectivesdefaultDevelopment objectives are usually secondary to political and security goals of Israel.
defaultA large 
defaultpart of the aid programme has been directed to security forces whose mandate is to police the Palestinian population rather than to defend their rights. Closures and illegal repression by Israel have been justified by some donors even if they are in contra
defaultdiction with the aid programme.
default&#xa0;
defaultPromote non-discriminationdefaultfor inclusive and stabledefaultsocietiesdefaultThere is clear-cut discrimination against Gaza and other parts of the OPT where local authorities or population disagree with PNA
default’
defaults policies. (In Gaza, 
defaultdevelopment cooperation has been frozen, leaving only emergency aid programmes in place).
default&#xa0;
defaultAlign with local prioritiesdefaultPalestinian actors (not only PNA) have been repeating that the priority is to end the occupation and, in the meantime, to improve social
default and economic conditions. Yet this priority has not been respected by donors.
defaultPractical coordinationdefaultCoordination with Palestinians has been minimal and erratic, even with the PNA. Coordination amongst donors is not systematic and does not cover some of 
defaultthe main actors, such as USAID.
default&#xa0;
defaultAct fast and stay engageddefaultResponses to crises have been ambiguous, especially with Gaza. Long-term commitments are unclear. Currently, aid commitments are being reduced.
default&#xa0;
defaultAvoid pockets of exclusiondefaultMany areas and sectors 
defaultin the OPT, particularly in Gaza, have been excluded by donors.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultIbrahim and Beaudet
default’
defaults analysis highlights that 
default“…
defaultas long as the occupation continues and the Israeli closure policy
default 
defaultdecimates the Palestinian economy, foreign aid can only address 
defaultshort-term humanitarian needs rather than long-term development goals that remain the priority of the Palestinians and the international donor community
default”
default. This is due to the underlying root causes of the conflict not being addressed, namely the occupation
default of Palestine by Israel.
